00:22:35,388 --> 00:22:37,788
Green and purple
top coming up...

506
00:22:37,857 --> 00:22:39,339
Doctor.

507
00:22:46,032 --> 00:22:47,164
He's seizing.

508
00:22:47,233 --> 00:22:49,211
What's the first thing
you do, Pravesh?

509
00:22:49,235 --> 00:22:51,101
Let's get some access.

510
00:22:51,154 --> 00:22:52,453
All right. Lorazepam.

511
00:22:52,521 --> 00:22:55,088
Four milligrams.
Go. Soon as possible,

512
00:22:55,158 --> 00:22:57,218
- get him on the monitor.
- What happened here? -Last I saw him,

513
00:22:57,242 --> 00:22:59,370
he was drinking his
colonoscopy prep solution.

514
00:22:59,394 --> 00:23:01,261
Where's Dr. Wilmot?

515
00:23:01,330 --> 00:23:03,410
Let me guess, you
paged him... No response.

516
00:23:15,844 --> 00:23:17,928
Dr. Carver.

517
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:19,980
Dr. Bell.

518
00:23:20,048 --> 00:23:21,281
It is an honor.

519
00:23:21,350 --> 00:23:23,684
Randy, please. The
pleasure's all mine.

520
00:23:23,752 --> 00:23:25,335
Welcome to my hospital.

521
00:23:25,405 --> 00:23:26,548
This is one hell of a hospital.

522
00:23:26,572 --> 00:23:28,167
Well, you haven't
seen anything yet.

523
00:23:28,191 --> 00:23:29,918
How 'bout a personal
tour before coffee?

524
00:23:29,942 --> 00:23:31,536
Does that tour include a
sneak peak at the Titian?

525
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:33,671
'Cause I am dying to get
my hands on one of them.

526
00:23:33,695 --> 00:23:36,175
Well, as long as you promise
to share how you were able to do

527
00:23:36,232 --> 00:23:38,849
a Kasai procedure
in under four hours.

528
00:23:38,918 --> 00:23:40,951
Dr. Carver. Wow, such an honor.

529
00:23:41,020 --> 00:23:43,065
- If I may, one question...
- Now-now is not the time.

530
00:23:43,089 --> 00:23:44,699
No, no. It's okay. What's
your question, son?

531
00:23:44,723 --> 00:23:46,684
Uh, your retrospective
study on risk factors for...

532
00:23:46,708 --> 00:23:49,059
How do you keep your
retransplantation rate

533
00:23:49,128 --> 00:23:51,762
- under 20%? -It's actually been 22%...
- This is not the time

534
00:23:51,831 --> 00:23:53,609
or place for any
kind of confrontation.

535
00:23:53,633 --> 00:23:55,410
I need to talk to
Dr. Wilmot. Whether or not

536
00:23:55,434 --> 00:23:57,378
there's a confrontation
or not is up to him.

537
00:23:57,402 --> 00:23:58,835
Just... let me handle it.

538
00:23:58,904 --> 00:24:00,737
Dr. Wilmot.

539
00:24:00,806 --> 00:24:03,407
I don't know what kind of drama
you got going on with Conrad,

540
00:24:03,476 --> 00:24:07,177
but get it the hell away from
Carver and me right now.

541
00:24:07,246 --> 00:24:09,045
Yes, sir.

542
00:24:09,115 --> 00:24:10,626
That's the first thing,
and the most important.

543
00:24:10,650 --> 00:24:12,649
Keep that in mind.

544
00:24:15,037 --> 00:24:16,970
Hey.

545
00:24:17,039 --> 00:24:18,483
I don't appreciate
you embarrassing me

546
00:24:18,507 --> 00:24:20,073
in front of Dr. Bell.

547
00:24:20,142 --> 00:24:22,425
You took anatomy class
in med school, right?

548
00:24:22,495 --> 00:24:25,078
Vestigial organs...

549
00:24:25,164 --> 00:24:27,142
- What are you rambling about?
- You know, like the appendix.

550
00:24:27,166 --> 00:24:29,477
The one in 20 people who have
it removed don't even miss it.

551
00:24:29,501 --> 00:24:33,053
Serves absolutely no purpose
in the human body anymore.

552
00:24:33,139 --> 00:24:35,372
Like certain doctors
here at Chastain.

553
00:24:35,441 --> 00:24:37,708
You really think you're
untouchable, don't you?

554
00:24:37,776 --> 00:24:40,693
What I think is you gave an
already malnourished patient

555
00:24:40,762 --> 00:24:44,247
a prep solution that exacerbated
his existing hyponatremia.

556
00:24:44,300 --> 00:24:47,134
And when he started seizing,
you were nowhere to be found.

557
00:24:47,203 --> 00:24:48,297
He's stable now, isn't he?

558
00:24:48,321 --> 00:24:49,252
Thanks to my intern.

559
00:24:49,322 --> 00:24:51,038
Good. Get an NG tube in there.

560
00:24:51,107 --> 00:24:52,484
We should be able to
get the solution straight

561
00:24:52,508 --> 00:24:54,691
into the digestive
system that way.

562
00:24:54,760 --> 00:24:56,410
You want to put Nigel through

563
00:24:56,478 --> 00:24:58,307
a nasogastric tube
insertion just for a test?

564
00:24:58,331 --> 00:25:00,742
If it means getting to the root
of his pain sooner than later,

565
00:25:00,766 --> 00:25:02,232
then, yes, I do.

566
00:25:02,301 --> 00:25:05,119
Look, I'm trying
to help the patient.

567
00:25:05,204 --> 00:25:07,444
Then why don't you try
actually listening to him?

568
00:25:17,383 --> 00:25:20,467
You did a good thing
getting Atiba to his family.

569
00:25:20,553 --> 00:25:22,473
At least he's
safe for one night.

570
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:24,320
I'm sorry I judged you.

571
00:25:24,389 --> 00:25:26,122
I didn't realize you judged me.

572
00:25:26,191 --> 00:25:27,702
It was all in my
inner monologue.

573
00:25:27,726 --> 00:25:29,660
Good to know.

574
00:25:29,728 --> 00:25:32,162
I would've wanted someone
to do the same for my sister.

575
00:25:32,230 --> 00:25:34,665
There were many nights
she didn't make it home.

576
00:25:34,733 --> 00:25:37,601
But she's been
sober for a year now.

577
00:25:39,137 --> 00:25:41,304
So, you're sleeping
with Jude now?

578
00:25:41,373 --> 00:25:43,740
What? Why would you say that?

579
00:25:43,809 --> 00:25:46,109
I'm really good at
reading body language.

580
00:25:46,162 --> 00:25:48,522
I mean, look, the guy's
attractive and he's nice...

581
00:25:48,564 --> 00:25:50,130
And safe,

582
00:25:50,216 --> 00:25:52,482
compared to
someone else we know.

583
00:25:52,551 --> 00:25:55,485
Look, Jude and I are just
becoming better friends.

584
00:25:55,554 --> 00:25:59,189
All right. So I guess that means
I can become "better friends"

585
00:25:59,258 --> 00:26:01,791
with Conrad now, right?

586
00:26:03,862 --> 00:26:07,431
I was joking.

587
00:26:07,499 --> 00:26:10,450
I-I'm sorry. I'm
still running late.

588
00:26:10,519 --> 00:26:13,203
What? Where are
you? I'll be there

589
00:26:13,272 --> 00:26:14,571
in less than ten minutes.

590
00:26:14,640 --> 00:26:17,558
I need you to drop me
at my place, right away.

591
00:26:17,626 --> 00:26:19,359
Yeah, sure.

592
00:26:24,450 --> 00:26:26,500
What are you doing?

593
00:26:26,568 --> 00:26:30,220
Wilmot ordered me to
put an NG tube in Nigel.

594
00:26:30,289 --> 00:26:31,905
What a surprise.

595
00:26:33,409 --> 00:26:35,725
He could have us both
cut from the program.

596
00:26:35,794 --> 00:26:37,605
Oh, man up. Where's
all that bravado

597
00:26:37,629 --> 00:26:38,929
you had on independence day?

598
00:26:38,998 --> 00:26:40,608
What happened to
"When someone's wrong,

599
00:26:40,632 --> 00:26:42,552
I'll be the first
one to tell 'em"?

600
00:26:43,252 --> 00:26:45,785
Well...

601
00:26:45,855 --> 00:26:48,405
I'm not so sure Wilmot's wrong.

602
00:26:51,460 --> 00:26:54,294
Get out of my way.

603
00:26:55,448 --> 00:26:57,330
Let me have it. I deserve it.

604
00:26:57,400 --> 00:26:59,210
When you asked for
24 hours, I didn't realize

605
00:26:59,234 --> 00:27:01,535
it would put me closer to
planning my own funeral.

606
00:27:01,621 --> 00:27:03,298
You said you could help
me. Now I'm worse off

607
00:27:03,322 --> 00:27:04,655
than when I came in.

608
00:27:08,811 --> 00:27:11,144
What are you doing?

609
00:27:11,213 --> 00:27:12,524
You're right. I should
have done a better job

610
00:27:12,548 --> 00:27:14,448
protecting you.

611
00:27:21,807 --> 00:27:23,440
Do you trust me?

612
00:27:24,459 --> 00:27:25,926
Yes.

613
00:27:25,994 --> 00:27:27,594
God knows why.

614
00:27:27,680 --> 00:27:29,112
Put your clothes on.

615
00:27:31,484 --> 00:27:34,301
Do I want to know
what you're doing?

616
00:27:34,370 --> 00:27:37,504
Wilmot can't test a
patient he can't find.

617
00:27:41,327 --> 00:27:43,076
Mina, what's going on?

618
00:27:43,162 --> 00:27:44,202
Thanks for the ride.

619
00:27:48,633 --> 00:27:50,833
I'm so sorry. We tried
to wait for you at home.

620
00:27:50,869 --> 00:27:52,714
No, it's my fault.
I was delayed.

621
00:27:52,738 --> 00:27:55,605
She won't stop throwing
up. It's never been this bad.

622
00:27:55,675 --> 00:27:57,653
These episodes can
recur multiple times a year.

623
00:27:57,677 --> 00:28:00,994
- Any abdominal pain?
- Yes. A lot.

624
00:28:02,981 --> 00:28:05,432
Here you go. Here you go, baby.

625
00:28:05,501 --> 00:28:08,502
- Tell me the pain, one to ten.
- Ten.

626
00:28:12,274 --> 00:28:14,574
You followed me?

627
00:28:14,643 --> 00:28:16,721
That call sounded urgent.
I thought I could help.

628
00:28:16,745 --> 00:28:17,822
Mina, what is going on in here?

629
00:28:17,846 --> 00:28:18,779
Do you have any
pain in your head?

630
00:28:18,847 --> 00:28:20,147
Just my stomach.

631
00:28:20,232 --> 00:28:21,509
Mm. I need one
tablet of ondansetron.

632
00:28:21,533 --> 00:28:22,782
Bottom drawer to the right.

633
00:28:22,851 --> 00:28:25,435
And one liter bag of IV
fluid from my backpack.

634
00:28:27,373 --> 00:28:29,700
Are you just going to stand
there or are you going to help?

635
00:28:34,547 --> 00:28:36,513
Mina, are these from Chastain?

636
00:28:45,524 --> 00:28:49,642
Okay, so this is one
test I haven't had.

637
00:28:49,729 --> 00:28:52,946
But, seriously, what
are we doing here?

638
00:28:53,014 --> 00:28:54,481
I'm hiding you where no doctor

639
00:28:54,550 --> 00:28:56,616
will voluntarily
show their face.

640
00:28:56,685 --> 00:28:58,768
A hospital waiting room?

641
00:28:59,905 --> 00:29:01,271
That is brilliant.

642
00:29:01,323 --> 00:29:04,457
And a damn sad
commentary on my profession.

643
00:29:04,527 --> 00:29:06,221
So, what's the
plan beyond hiding?

644
00:29:06,245 --> 00:29:07,411
I'm gonna listen.

645
00:29:07,480 --> 00:29:10,330
I've reviewed all your
old medical records.

646
00:29:10,399 --> 00:29:13,650
Now I want your patient
history directly from you.

647
00:29:13,718 --> 00:29:16,970
Doesn't matter how small
the detail... bore me with it.

648
00:29:17,039 --> 00:29:19,468
You went to all this trouble
and all we're gonna do is talk?

649
00:29:19,492 --> 00:29:21,608
Patient's words over tests.

650
00:29:21,676 --> 00:29:25,495
90% of the time, they give
you the answers you need.

651
00:29:25,548 --> 00:29:27,547
Hmm.

652
00:29:27,616 --> 00:29:30,366
Maybe.

653
00:29:30,436 --> 00:29:32,569
I have to say, you're
not what I expected.

654
00:29:32,638 --> 00:29:34,070
Yeah? What'd you expect?

655
00:29:34,139 --> 00:29:37,073
Frankly, less warmth, more ego.

656
00:29:37,142 --> 00:29:38,708
Well...

657
00:29:38,777 --> 00:29:40,755
Your surgeons are
lucky to have you as chief.

658
00:29:40,779 --> 00:29:43,124
- I hope they appreciate you.
- Well, y-you're very kind.

659
00:29:43,148 --> 00:29:45,715
But I can tell you what they
do appreciate is the autonomy

660
00:29:45,784 --> 00:29:47,317
and the extensive OR time.

661
00:29:47,385 --> 00:29:50,320
And, you know, for
the best of the best,

662
00:29:50,388 --> 00:29:51,933
just a membership
to the Blackburn Club.

663
00:29:51,957 --> 00:29:53,590
Wow.

664
00:29:53,659 --> 00:29:55,437
A lot of benefits to
working here at Chastain.

665
00:29:55,461 --> 00:29:57,038
- It's a great place to be.
- Well...

666
00:29:57,062 --> 00:29:59,513
I'm curious. Uh...

667
00:29:59,582 --> 00:30:03,266
how are your surgical
error and complication rates?

668
00:30:03,335 --> 00:30:04,767
Excuse me?

669
00:30:04,837 --> 00:30:07,270
Well, I'm leaving St. Grace
for a bunch of reasons,

670
00:30:07,339 --> 00:30:09,806
and, to be honest,
accountability's a big one.

671
00:30:09,875 --> 00:30:11,936
They refused to even
consider my recommendations

672
00:30:11,960 --> 00:30:15,728
for tracking surgical error
rates, among other things.

673
00:30:15,797 --> 00:30:17,764
Well, so-so what
you're looking for

674
00:30:17,832 --> 00:30:19,610
is a place that's
willing to embrace that.

675
00:30:19,634 --> 00:30:21,846
Transparency and accountability
force us to weed out the bad

676
00:30:21,870 --> 00:30:24,387
and grow the good.

677
00:30:24,440 --> 00:30:27,774
This one doctor at St.
Grace had patients die

678
00:30:27,843 --> 00:30:30,343
from complications every
time he did a bypass.

679
00:30:30,412 --> 00:30:33,296
No one even noticed.

680
00:30:33,365 --> 00:30:35,732
Except me. I noticed.

681
00:30:35,801 --> 00:30:38,785
That's incredible.

682
00:30:38,871 --> 00:30:41,137
I'm telling you, it's
like they say, you know,

683
00:30:41,206 --> 00:30:43,523
the truth never
gets out of the OR.

684
00:31:00,726 --> 00:31:03,860
Well, you are just
full of surprises.

685
00:31:03,929 --> 00:31:05,628
How's Shalisha?

686
00:31:05,697 --> 00:31:07,713
Cyclical vomiting syndrome.

687
00:31:07,782 --> 00:31:10,250
She'll be fine once she
finishes her IV treatment.

688
00:31:10,319 --> 00:31:11,384
Mina...

689
00:31:11,453 --> 00:31:12,252
Save me the lecture.

690
00:31:12,321 --> 00:31:13,653
I can't.

691
00:31:13,721 --> 00:31:15,199
You're treating
patients from your home.

692
00:31:15,223 --> 00:31:17,001
You're taking
supplies from Chastain.

693
00:31:17,025 --> 00:31:18,669
Those drugs are all
free samples from reps.

694
00:31:18,693 --> 00:31:21,778
Free samples given to Chastain.
Regardless, you could lose

695
00:31:21,830 --> 00:31:24,764
your medical license for
treating people in your home.

696
00:31:24,833 --> 00:31:26,528
Hell, Mina, you
could lose your visa.

697
00:31:26,552 --> 00:31:27,784
I'm not a fool. I know that.

698
00:31:27,853 --> 00:31:29,731
But am I supposed
to look the other way

699
00:31:29,755 --> 00:31:32,150
while people in my community
are dying from treatable illnesses?

700
00:31:32,174 --> 00:31:33,973
So send them to a clinic.

701
00:31:34,042 --> 00:31:35,992
What clinic?

702
00:31:36,061 --> 00:31:38,461
All the big hospitals are
closing their local clinics

703
00:31:38,530 --> 00:31:40,547
left and right for
profit reasons.

704
00:31:40,615 --> 00:31:42,260
And it's not fair. But if
you lose your license,

705
00:31:42,284 --> 00:31:45,351
you're not gonna
help anybody. Ever.

706
00:31:51,910 --> 00:31:55,845
My uncle, Onoche,

707
00:31:55,914 --> 00:31:57,847
he was a brilliant man.

708
00:31:57,916 --> 00:31:59,899
Like a second father to me.

709
00:31:59,968 --> 00:32:03,503
He was a surgeon
here in the U.S., and...

710
00:32:03,589 --> 00:32:05,266
when he'd visit
Nigeria on holiday,

711
00:32:05,290 --> 00:32:08,024
he'd bring my cousins
clothes and candy.

712
00:32:08,093 --> 00:32:12,913
For me, he'd bring
medical books and gadgets.

713
00:32:12,981 --> 00:32:15,882
On his last visit home,
he had a heart attack.

714
00:32:15,951 --> 00:32:18,552
A heart attack he
would have survived

715
00:32:18,620 --> 00:32:21,788
if he had access to
proper health care

716
00:32:21,856 --> 00:32:24,157
and not been in a
hospital in Arondizuogu

717
00:32:24,226 --> 00:32:27,760
without a working defibrillator.

718
00:32:31,767 --> 00:32:33,967
I think that's the most
words you've said, ever,

719
00:32:34,002 --> 00:32:36,619
in the past three
years I've known you.

720
00:32:46,799 --> 00:32:48,949
Don't get used to it.

721
00:32:55,374 --> 00:32:57,874
<i>I don't know how I
was still standing.</i>

722
00:32:57,943 --> 00:33:01,544
It hurt, but I still
finished the show.

723
00:33:01,597 --> 00:33:04,114
My rendition of Albrecht's
Act II variation was

724
00:33:04,183 --> 00:33:05,782
"just perfection."

725
00:33:05,851 --> 00:33:07,834
At least, according
to The<i> Times.</i>

726
00:33:07,903 --> 00:33:09,285
I would've paid to see that.

727
00:33:14,008 --> 00:33:15,741
Colleague issues?

728
00:33:15,810 --> 00:33:17,710
Father issues.

729
00:33:17,779 --> 00:33:20,913
You're talking to a male
dancer about daddy issues?

730
00:33:20,982 --> 00:33:23,433
Bet my old man was way worse.

731
00:33:23,502 --> 00:33:24,767
Oh, you think so, huh?

732
00:33:24,836 --> 00:33:25,981
My dad couldn't wrap his head

733
00:33:26,005 --> 00:33:27,816
around me wanting
to dance ballet.

734
00:33:27,840 --> 00:33:30,624
So he forced me to go
out for football instead.

735
00:33:30,709 --> 00:33:33,459
He'd train me by making
me run stadium stairs

736
00:33:33,545 --> 00:33:35,445
carrying buckets of sand.

737
00:33:35,514 --> 00:33:37,947
My legs would burn,

738
00:33:38,016 --> 00:33:40,950
my lungs exploding.

739
00:33:41,019 --> 00:33:43,020
I was, like, 15
years old at the time,

740
00:33:43,088 --> 00:33:45,305
and I thought I
was going to die.

741
00:33:45,373 --> 00:33:48,308
Never thought just inhaling air

742
00:33:48,376 --> 00:33:50,944
could be so excruciating.

743
00:33:51,013 --> 00:33:52,795
But my father didn't care.

744
00:33:52,865 --> 00:33:55,165
He just kept pushing.

745
00:33:55,234 --> 00:33:57,234
My dad was so
bad, I went to fight

746
00:33:57,302 --> 00:33:59,619
in Afghanistan for
peace and quiet.

747
00:34:04,409 --> 00:34:06,826
You said you were 15
when this happened?

748
00:34:06,912 --> 00:34:09,178
Yeah.

749
00:34:09,247 --> 00:34:11,698
Funny thing is, my dad
still thinks I'm a wuss.

750
00:34:11,766 --> 00:34:14,184
Joke's on him. He doesn't
get how much strength

751
00:34:14,252 --> 00:34:16,052
it takes to do ballet.

752
00:34:16,121 --> 00:34:17,732
Was that the first time
you felt pain like that?

753
00:34:17,756 --> 00:34:19,822
Sure, yeah.

754
00:34:19,891 --> 00:34:22,158
But it would always go
away after the workout.

755
00:34:22,227 --> 00:34:23,926
Huh.

756
00:34:23,979 --> 00:34:25,890
Was your initial pain
centered in your diaphragm,

